	<div class="main-content-wrap">

		
			
				<article class="post-5815724 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry tag-coronavirus tag-covid-19 channel-science no-image bgr-style-_default">

					<div class="row page-header content-section">
						<div class="columns">
														<div class="primary-category channel-color-background">Science</div>
							<h1 class="entry-title">Scientists warn that Trump is wrong: Warm weather won&#8217;t kill coronavirus</h1>
													</div>
					</div>

					<div class="row content-section">
						<div class="main-content columns">

							<header class="page-header">
																<div class="featured-image">
									<div class="row">
										<div class="columns">
											<img width="782" height="521" src="https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=782" class="attachment-single-featured-desktop size-single-featured-desktop wp-post-image" alt="Coronavirus USA" srcset="https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=782 782w, https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1564 1564w, https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=150 150w, https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=300 300w, https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=768 768w, https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1024 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 782px) 100vw, 782px" data-attachment-id="5806578" data-permalink="https://bgr.com/2020/03/24/coronavirus-news-today-quarantine-kit-best-deals/coronavirus-quarantine/" data-orig-file="https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all" data-orig-size="1600,1067" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="coronavirus-quarantine" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=300" data-large-file="https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine.jpg?quality=98&amp;strip=all&amp;w=834" title="Coronavirus USA" />										</div>
									</div>
								</div>
																<div class="row">
									<div class="columns">
										<div class="entry-meta clearfix">
											<div class="byline">
	<div class="author-name">
		By <a href="https://bgr.com/author/chris-smith/">Chris Smith</a>
					<a class="twitter" href="https://twitter.com/chris_writes"><span>@chris_writes</span></a>
			</div>
	<div class="posted-on">April 9th, 2020 at 2:22 PM</div>
</div>
										</div>
									</div>
								</div>
							</header>

							<div class="page-content">
								<div class="row">
									<div class="columns">
										<div class="entry-content">
											<ul><li><strong>Members of the National Academy of Sciences committee sent a letter to the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy warning the administration that warmer weather won&rsquo;t stop the spread of the novel coronavirus.</strong></li>
<li><strong>President Trump said in the past that warmer weather will make the virus disappear &ldquo;miraculously,&rdquo; starting in April.</strong></li>
<li><strong>COVID-19 caseloads in countries with warmer climates, as well as coronavirus cases from warm US states like California and Florida, prove the virus can be very infectious regardless of the weather.</strong></li>
<li><strong><a href="https://bgr.com">Visit BGR&rsquo;s homepage for more stories</a>.</strong></li>
</ul><hr><p>President Trump has said on more than one occasion that warmer weather will kill the novel coronavirus. He&rsquo;s wrong. &ldquo;When it gets a little warmer, it miraculously goes away,&rdquo; <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/11/politics/trump-new-hampshire-rally/index.html" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">he said</a> at a rally in New Hampshire on February 10th. The US had only 12 cases at the time, although countries from warmer climates, including Australia and Singapore, were providing direct evidence that warmer weather would not kill the virus or reduce its contagiousness. In total, there were more than <a href="https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">42,000 cases</a> in the world on that day, most of them in mainland China.</p>
<p>	<div class="admz" id="adm-inline-article-ad-1">
					<div class="adma google-publisher" data-device="Desktop" data-width="300">
				
<div class="pmc-adm-goog-pub-div ">
	<div id="gpt-dsk-ros-mid-article-uid0" class="ad-rotatable adw-300 adh-250"></div>
		</div>
			</div>
				</div>
</p>
<p>Two months and <a href="https://coronavirus.app/map" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">nearly 1.5 million cases</a> later, it&rsquo;s increasingly clear that weather alone can&rsquo;t defeat the virus. The increasing caseloads in Florida and California also prove that point. Scientists have even more data on the SARS-CoV-2 survivability in various environments, and some of them have sent the White House an official letter to warn that a heatwave will do little to stop the COVID-19 spread.<span id="more-5815724"></span></p>
<p><div class="dont-miss" style="background-image: url(&quot;https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2018/10/amazon-sign-boxes-1.jpg?quality=98&#038;strip=all&#038;w=782&#038;h=602&#038;crop=1&quot;)"><a href="https://bgr.com/2020/04/09/amazon-deals-of-the-day-on-apr-9/"><strong>Don&#039;t Miss<span>:</span></strong> <span class="title">Today&#8217;s top deals: Rare AirPods Pro sale, Anker blowout, DIY face masks, Fire TV Stick 4K for $25, smart plugs for $6, more</span></a></div></p>
<p>Members of the National Academy of Sciences committee <a href="https://www.nap.edu/read/25771/chapter/1" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">sent the letter</a> to the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy, explaining there&rsquo;s not enough evidence to suggest that the novel coronavirus will stop spreading in the coming months just because it&rsquo;s warmer outside.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There is some evidence to suggest that [coronavirus] may transmit less efficiently in environments with higher ambient temperature and humidity; however, given the lack of host immunity globally, this reduction in transmission efficiency may not lead to a significant reduction in disease spread without the concomitant adoption of major public health interventions,&rdquo; the letter said. &ldquo;Given that countries currently in &lsquo;summer&rsquo; climates, such as Australia and Iran, are experiencing rapid virus spread, a decrease in cases with increases in humidity and temperature elsewhere should not be assumed.&rdquo;</p>
<p>	<div class="admz" id="adm-inline-article-ad-2">
					<div class="adma google-publisher" data-device="Desktop" data-width="300">
				
<div class="pmc-adm-goog-pub-div ">
	<div id="gpt-ros-mid-article2-uid1" class="ad-rotatable adw-300 adh-250"></div>
		</div>
			</div>
				</div>
</p>
<p>The letter noted that a study from China revealed that the virus still spreads exponentially under extreme temperature and humidity conditions. Each infected person would still be spreading the disease to nearly two more people. The letter also notes that some studies showed reduced transmission in warmer and more humid conditions, but it&rsquo;s not enough. One researcher showed that the novel coronavirus could live longer than the flu, tuberculosis, and the coronavirus type that caused the SARS epidemic nearly two decades ago.</p>
<p>Other studies that measured the time the new coronavirus can survive on different surfaces also looked at how the virus performed at different temperatures. One of the conclusions was that only extreme heat can kill the virus, the kind of heat we could never survive in. The virus was inactivated in just 5 minutes at 70&deg;C/158&deg;F. A study from 2003 also showed that the SARS coronavirus could survive at up to &ldquo;[37&deg;C/98.6&deg;F] for at least 2h without remarkable change in the infectious ability in cells.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Although we can hope weather will make some contribution to the reduction in transmission, we can&rsquo;t rely on it alone,&rdquo; infectious disease specialist at Vanderbilt University Medical Center Dr. William Schaffner <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/08/health/coronavirus-stays-warmer-weather/index.html" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">told <em>CNN</em></a>. &ldquo;We have to continue to employ social distancing and other measures to reduce transmission,&rdquo; the doctor, who isn&rsquo;t a member of the NAS committee, added.</p>											<div class="featured-image-source">
	<span class="description img-caption"><span class="source">Image Source: Deliris/Shutterstock</span></span></div>
																						<div class="entry-tags">
												Tags: <a href="https://bgr.com/tag/coronavirus/" rel="tag">coronavirus</a>, <a href="https://bgr.com/tag/covid-19/" rel="tag">covid-19</a>											</div>
											<div class="author-bio">
	<div class="author-bio-image-container with-avatar">
		<img src="https://boygeniusreport.files.wordpress.com/2013/11/chris-smith-125x125.jpg" height="52px" width="47px">
	</div>
	<div class="author-bio-text">
		Chris Smith started writing about gadgets as a hobby, and before he knew it he was sharing his views on tech stuff with readers around the world. Whenever he's not writing about gadgets he miserably fails to stay away from them, although he desperately tries. But that's not necessarily a bad thing.	</div>
